	abstract = {Traditional vocabulary teaching in junior high school English often suffers from superficial review, low interactivity, and limited long-term retention. The emergence of Artificial Intelligence Generated Content (AIGC) and machine learning technologies offers new possibilities for addressing these challenges through multimodal and data-driven instructional design. This study aims to design and evaluate an AIGC-enabled text-to-song-MV instructional path for junior high school English vocabulary review, incorporating the Random Forest algorithm to analyze learning outcomes and validate intervention effectiveness through a controlled experiment. The study employed a quasi-experimental design with 80 seventh-grade students from two parallel classes assigned to the experimental (n=40) and control groups (n=40). The experimental group received AIGC-supported song-MV vocabulary instruction, while the control group followed traditional methods. A Random Forest model was applied to analyze pre-test and post-test scores, student behavior logs, and questionnaire responses. Statistical analyses included paired t-tests, independent t-tests, and ANCOVA to validate the results. In the experiment, the Random Forest model achieved 86.25% accuracy in classifying learning outcomes. The experimental group showed significantly greater vocabulary gain (+17.5, p<0.001, Cohen’s d=2.42) compared to the control group (+7.4). Feature importance analysis revealed pre-test scores (41%), MV interaction (36%), and lyric creation (23%) as key predictors. ANCOVA showed the instructional method accounted for 50% of score variance (partial η<sup>2</sup>=0.50). Questionnaire results indicated high levels of engagement (mean=4.45/5.0) and learning satisfaction (mean=4.55/5.0). This demonstrates that the AIGC-supported text-to-song-MV path significantly enhances vocabulary retention, engagement, and overall learning efficiency. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
