	affiliations = {College of Teacher Education, Huzhou University, Huzhou, China},
	abstract = {With the rapid growth of online education, large volumes of student behavioral data are continuously collected, providing new opportunities for quantitative assessment of learning quality. However, data from elementary students are typically highly heterogeneous, noisy, and incomplete, posing significant challenges for real-time prediction and accurate evaluation. To address these challenges, this study proposes a ClusterConstrained Gradient Boosting Regression Tree (CC-GBRT) model that integrates ensemble learning with clustering constraints for learning quality prediction and dynamic assessment. A Gaussian Copula-based multivariate data simulation method was first employed to construct a statistically consistent and privacy-preserving learning behavior dataset. Subsequently, the K -means algorithm was used to partition the behavioral space, and local regression models were trained within each cluster to capture behavioral diversity and enhance prediction stability and precision. In addition, a dynamic Learning Quality Rating (LQR) indicator was designed to quantify students' engagement and performance variation in real time. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed CC-GBRT model outperforms traditional methods, reducing the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) by approximately 15-17%, and increasing the coefficient of determination (R<sup>2</sup>) by about 2%. Furthermore, the model exhibits strong robustness under noisy data conditions, while the LQR metric achieves a Pearson correlation coefficient of 0.84 with actual academic performance, confirming its reliability in learning quality monitoring and assessment. Overall, this study provides a datadriven and interpretable framework for real-time evaluation of online learning quality, offering methodological insights for the intelligent transformation of basic education.  © 2025 IEEE.},
