	abstract = {Student engagement involves participation, motivation, and emotional involvement, and has implications for academic performance. Machine learning (ML) can predict student engagement through big data analytics can offer insights for personalized learning and interventions, revealing trends beyond traditional methods. The research investigates the purpose of ML and big data by optimizing the prediction of student engagement. The dataset from the open source is utilized which consists of many academic and behavioral features of students. In the pre-processing phase, the data is normalized with Min-Max, which scales data into the appropriate range to perform the model more effectively. It makes feature extraction using Principal Component Analysis (PCA), which reduces the dimensions of information but keeps vital components of the data. The novel Shark Nose Optimizer tuned-Dynamic Support Vector Regression (SNO-DSVR) approach to increase student engagement predicting accuracy. SNO significantly refines the DSVR model also enhances the optimization as well as the predictive abilities of the method. The efficiency of the method is compared against existing approaches based on the main performance metrics which are accuracy 93.15%, precision 95.00%, recall 94.12%, AUC 97.00%, and log loss 21.40%. The result strongly points to the SNO-DSVR outperforming others in correctly predicting student engagement, indicating the possibility of its implementation in educational analytics for enhanced student outcomes. © 2025 IEEE.},
