	doi = {10.1109/FIE63693.2025.11328252},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033055798?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Virginia Military Institute, Computer & Information Sciences Department, Lexington, VA, United States; Lexington, VA, United States},
	abstract = {This full research paper explores using artificial intelligence to automate student engagement detection in face-toface and online learning environments. Monitoring engagement, especially in large-scale classrooms such as MOOCs, presents challenges due to the lack of real-time feedback and the difficulty of observing individual behaviors. Traditional methods like surveys rely on subjective, self-reported data and cannot capture engagement dynamics over time. These challenges highlight the need for scalable, real-time monitoring systems to complement and support traditional methods. Guided by Engagement Theory, this research examines how behavioral, cognitive, and emotional engagement-manifested through attentiveness, participation, boredom, or distraction-can be visually recorded in images and analyzed and classified using AI. It examines three critical questions: What are the current research trends, and who are the main contributors in this field? How effectively can deep learning models classify student behavior as engaged or disengaged? How does the integration of machine learning with deep learning models enhance the performance of engagement detection? The study involved a bibliographic analysis and two experiments to answer these research questions. Around one thousand publications between 1999 and 2024 were collected from the Scopus database and quantitatively analyzed to understand the research landscape in this domain. In the first experiment, three wellknown deep learning models (MobileNet, VGG16, and ResNet50) were trained directly on our curated and augmented dataset of 6,479 student images. In the second experiment, three sets of image features were extracted using the three deep learning models and combined into one feature set. The combined feature set was then used to train and test different machine learning algorithms. A web-based system was implemented to integrate the AI models into a user-friendly platform that includes a dashboard with analytics for real-time engagement monitoring and visualizations. The bibliographic analysis identified research trends, key authors and institutions, and research gaps, and the findings guided our study experiments. In Experiment 1, VGG16 achieved the highest accuracy at 93.3%. In Experiment 2, integrating deep learning with machine learning improved classification performance, with Logistic Regression achieving 96% accuracy, outperforming all other models. Additional performance metrics were analyzed, including precision, recall, and F1 score. This work contributes to computing and engineering education by equipping educators and decision-makers with an AI-enabled, data-driven approach to monitoring student engagement. By operationalizing Engagement Theory, this research connects theory, research, and practice, supporting the creation of responsive learning environments. Future research will explore more AI techniques and modalities like video and voice analysis. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {Assessment tools; Engagement; Learning modality; Learning technology; Massive Open Online Classes (MOOCs)},
