	abstract = {In today's world learners have access to a plethora of information in online learning platforms to hone their skills in different fields. Although a large number of choices may seem good, but it also leads to choice overload. Recommender systems (RS) can play a pivotal role in personalizing e-learning experiences by providing tailored content through various techniques. One commonly employed technique in such systems is collaborative filtering (CF). In this study, we utilize autoencoders within a CF framework to suggest course modules to learners. Our approach demonstrates superior performance in enhancing personalized learning experiences, addressing challenges posed by high-dimensional and sparse data. Empirical results confirm the effectiveness of our model, surpassing traditional methods like KNN, SVD, SVD++, and NMF in terms of accuracy. This research contributes to advancing e-learning recommendation systems, highlighting the potential of autoencoder-based collaborative filtering in optimizing learner engagement and performance. © 2024 IEEE.},
