	abstract = {Ensuring student success in higher education institutions is paramount for both individual development and societal advancement. However, traditional methods for identifying and supporting at-risk students often lack the precision and timeliness necessary for effective intervention. The potential for machine learning to revolutionize early warning systems and intervention strategies is increasingly recognized, offering the ability to analyze complex datasets and predict student outcomes with greater precision. This study aims to conduct a comprehensive thematic literature review of existing research on artificial intelligence based early warning and intervention models for student success in institution's of higher learning. There is a pressing need for robust, data-driven approaches that can provide actionable insights to the academic staff, administrators and other stake holders within the University. To that end, electronic bibliographic databases and resources, including Access World News, IEEE, ProQuest, Science Direct, World Bank Group, Taylor & Francis Journals, Springer Collection, SABINET African Journals and Scopus, were systematically searched to identify peer-reviewed publications published in English between January 2006 and March 2025. The thematic review presented presents the total number of articles retrieved, establishes clear inclusion criteria, and synthesizes the main themes emerging from the selected studies. This review considers the machine learning algorithms employed, performance metrics utilized, application domains, methodological approaches, input and output parameters, and key findings. Furthermore, this paper will examine the current state of machine learning applications in predicting student success, focusing on the identification of at-risk students and the development of targeted intervention strategies. It will also discuss the challenges and future directions for Machine Learning-driven early warning systems in higher education, ultimately providing a comprehensive overview of the field. © 2025 IEEE.},
